'''Elements Software''', formerly known as Helveta, is a [[supply chain management software]] company based in [[Abingdon-on-Thames|Abingdon]], [[Oxfordshire]], [[England]]. With revenues of £2.1 million in 2010, it has been recognized for its work in [[forestry]] conservation, specifically [[illegal logging]] prevention.
==History== Patrick Newton founded Helveta in Abingdon, Oxfordshire in 2004. The company developed supply-chain management software Control Intelligence (CI) World to allow customers to track assets. Supported industries include [[biofuel]], [[food processing]], and forestry.<ref>{{cite news|title=Company Overview of Helveta Ltd.|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/research/stocks/private/snapshot.asp?privcapId=9709065|accessdate=2015-08-30|work=Bloomberg Businessweek}}</ref> In 2010 Helveta's revenues reached £2.1 million.<ref name=Jacobs />
In 2008, the Forest Development Authority hired Helveta and SGS, an inspection firm, to develop a technology [[barcode]] scanning system to track lumber in [[Liberia]], where the [[United Nations]] banned the logging trade in 2003.<ref name=economist>{{cite news|title=Protected by bars|url=http://www.economist.com/node/10804107|accessdate=2015-08-30|work=The Economist|date=2008-03-06}}</ref> Helveta also earned clients in the [[Democratic Republic of the Congo]]<ref>{{cite news|last1=Henley|first1=Will|title=Tracking timber: could new technology help clean up the supply chain?|url=https://www.theguardian.com/sustainable-business/tracking-timber-new-technology-supply-chain|accessdate=2015-08-30|work=The Guardian|date=2013-08-14}}</ref> and [[Cameroon]], where a similar project ran from 2008 to 2011. The Cameroon project met many of its goals but failed to secure a long-term commitment in part due to changing government authorities.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Lewis|first1=Jerome|last2=Nkuintchua|first2=Teodyl|title=Accessible technologies and FPIC: independent monitoring with forest communities in Cameroon|date=2012|publisher=International Institute for Education and Development|pages=152–163|url=http://pubs.iied.org/pdfs/14618IIED.pdf#page=153|accessdate=2015-08-30}}</ref>
=== Leadership === Karim Peer is the [[Chief Executive Officer]] (CEO) after replacing Newton in 2011.<ref name=Jacobs>{{cite news|last1=Jacobs|first1=Rose|title=Chipping away at deforestation|url=http://www.ft.com/intl/cms/s/0/60428106-6e57-11e1-b98d-00144feab49a.html#axzz3kLSZxFlo|accessdate=2015-08-30|work=Financial Times|date=2012-03-20}}</ref>
==Awards and recognition== The [[Financial Times]] recognized Helveta as a "Boldness in Business" 2012 award winner for finding profit-making opportunities in sustainable development.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Authers|first1=John|title=Good judgment|url=http://www.ft.com/cms/s/0/826e2616-6e4f-11e1-b98d-00144feab49a.html|accessdate=2015-08-30|work=The Financial Times|date=2012-03-20}}</ref> In 2015, Helveta was selected as a top ten finalist in the [[Ernst & Young|EY]] Startup Challenge.<ref>{{cite web|title=Winning tech firms announced for the 2nd EY Startup Challenge|url=http://www.cambridgenetwork.co.uk/news/winning-tech-firms-ey-startup-challenge/|website=Cambridge Network|accessdate=2015-08-30}}</ref>
