{{Use Canadian English|date=January 2013}} {{Infobox CanadianMP | honorific-prefix = | name = René Soetens | honorific-suffix = | image = | riding = [[Ontario (electoral district)|Ontario electoral district]] | parliament = Canadian | term_start = 1988 | term_end = 1993 | predecessor = [[Thomas Fennell (politician)|Tom Fennell]] | successor = [[Dan McTeague]] | birth_date = {{birth date and age|df=yes|1948|09|07}} | birth_place = [[Eindhoven]], [[Netherlands]] | death_date = | death_place = | party = [[Progressive Conservative Party of Canada|Progressive Conservative]] | spouse = | residence = [[Toronto]] | profession = Businessman | religion = }}{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2013}} '''René John Soetens''' (born 7 September 1948) was a member of the [[House of Commons of Canada]] from 1988 to 1993. His background was in business and sales.
Rene was elected to [[Ajax, Ontario|Town of Ajax]] Council in 1980 and re-elected 1982 and 1985. He was elected in the [[Canadian federal election, 1988|1988 federal election]] at the [[Ontario (electoral district)|Ontario electoral district]] for the [[Progressive Conservative Party of Canada|Progressive Conservative party]]. He served in the [[34th Canadian Parliament]] but lost to [[Dan McTeague]] of the [[Liberal Party of Canada|Liberal Party]] in the [[Canadian federal election, 1993|1993 federal election]].
Soetens also made an unsuccessful bid to return to national Parliament in the [[Canadian federal election, 2004|2004 federal election]] at the [[Ajax—Pickering]] [[electoral district]]. He is president and owner of Con-Test, a national certification company specializing in the testing of controlled environments found in research facilities, hospitals, pharmaceutical drug manufacturing and associated cleanrooms.
